function findClosestElements(arr, k, x) {
    let left = 0;
    let right = arr.length - k;

    while (left < right) {
        let mid = left + ((right - left) >> 1);
        if (x - arr[mid] > arr[mid + k] - x) {
            left = mid + 1;
        } else {
            right = mid;
        }
    }

    return arr.slice(left, left + k);
}
```

    The algorithm uses a binary search to find the subarray of length `k` with the closest numbers to `x`. 

1. Initialize the `left` pointer to the beginning of the array and the `right` pointer to the end of the array minus `k`.
2. While the `left` pointer is less than the `right` pointer:
    a. Calculate the `mid` index.
    b. Compare the difference between `arr[mid]` and `x`, and the difference between `arr[mid + k]` and `x`.
    c. If the difference at `mid` is greater, update `left` to `mid + 1`, otherwise update `right` to `mid`.
3. Once the binary search is complete, the result will be the subarray of length `k` starting at the `left` index.

This algorithm has a time complexity of O(log(n)) where n is the length of the input array, as it uses binary search to locate the closest elements. The space complexity is also O(1) since only a constant number of variables are used.

